segments.text: Harrington Building, who has been in the College of Education before it was even a College of Education.

He's going to share some ideas and some thoughts and some perceptions of the things that have happened over the last 20-some years and fill me in on what you feel has impacted this college and some of the changes, some of the things that have
change mainly, I guess, is what I'm interested in.
I'm interested in your own personal perception versus what I can find in some of the books.
I want to know a little bit about your feelings and about the culture and the climate of this college and how it has evolved.
Well, that's a very broad, open-ended kind of question.
But let me say that I think major
impact on the college has been the two deans that have been part of one that was part of the history and one that was current.
Dean Hubert, who of course later became chancellor, had a strong background in education and it was obvious that he was
highly qualified to help this institution develop a college of education.
And so his perspective, particularly in terms of how A&M might serve the state of Texas, I think was very important.
Did you have any input back then when this was in the process of being
bounced around, were you able to have some?
There were a series of meetings.
And in fact, there was a meeting in Caldwell at the motel there, which name I don't remember at the moment.
The Surrey Inn?
Surrey Inn.
And we had a three-day session over there.
And who was involved in that?
Well, I think a fairly substantial number of the faculty in the college, in the Department of Education at that time.
I don't know that all were, but certainly a majority were.
And out of that, I think that Gilbert used the input from those from that session as at least
a significant part of the development of the plans for the college.
A similar meeting took place in Galveston, I think perhaps at the end of the first year that after the college had been formulated.
And that involved, again, perhaps selective faculty members from the college, but also
included quite a number of school superintendents and other people from out in the field that helped to make suggestions as to what they thought this college of education ought to be like.
So your initial statement had to do with the two deans and Hubert being, of course, the catalyst that got it.
I think that I would add to my comments a little bit more reference to Dean Corrigan, who, of course, has been our second dean in almost 20 years.
We're 18 years.
When I finish this, it'll be 20 years.
It'll be 20 years.
And so two deans.
for that period of time, a pretty good record.
Either we have been easy on our deans, or they have been either very enduring or something.
Is the lifespan of a dean fairly short on the average?
I know for superintendents it is, but...
I think the tenure of deans is longer than school superintendents.
But Dean Corrigan brought, I think, a different perspective from his
more national experience and quite a different style of serving as dean.
And I think he has challenged the faculty at the college to be abreast of what is going on and what those national
issues may be in order to formulate this college in the direction in which it might really have important characters.
Has that changed, in your opinion, how outsiders view the College of Education since he has come on with this perspective?
Has it focused or has it changed that?
I don't know that I have real evidence of that.
I have an assumption that
that since Dean Corrigan is better known nationally that there are more people who know about Texas A&M and understand its program and have had continuing contacts with with our Dean so that
We probably have continued to be better known.
And I think Dean Corrigan has added greatly to that.
And the mission of the college, of course, is the teaching, research, and service.
In your perception, how has that changed or has it changed in the two administrations, the focus or the?
I don't think that's changed.
That's very much a part of the land grant tradition, and certainly was the focus from our beginning in education.
Although, of course, it obviously is not limited to our particular college.
A college of education, I think, does have more
contact with the field than some colleges.
Certainly not the only one that does, but it has a continuing relationship with people out in the field.
Dr. Hawkins, is there a variation within departments as to how much contact there is with the field?
Or is it up to the department heads how much they focus on that service versus the research or the teaching or whatever?
Well, I think the nature of each department is such that it does.
It may make a difference in terms of the people in the field that are contacted.
But I wouldn't want to suggest that any single department would have less contact in this department.
Since we are a department-based state administration,

always prided ourselves and endeavored to maintain as strong a contact with school superintendents and other administrators in the field as possible and we have had over the years our so-called june conference and some other activities school board workshop that has
that's been part of our contact mechanism.
There has been tremendous growth, obviously, since you came here within this college and, of course, within the department.
Has that affected, to any extent, your work with students?
Has it made any difference?
I think so.
I think that it has tended to make each of us, as faculty members in this department,
more specialized.
When I first came, three of us at least had been superintendents.
The assumption was that we needed to be able to make contact with superintendents.
But also, this seemed to suggest that we were pretty much generalists and that we felt
and need and perhaps a capability in identifying with education in a broad sense.
As we expanded the number of faculty members, we sought to do that in terms of people who were specialists and who were expected to fill that kind of role within the department.
Although in recent years, we've begun to focus back, in a sense, with several people at one time or another teaching the same course.
Nevertheless, we still have our identity where we fit in the department program.
You were department head for a number of years.
What did you look for in your faculty members, or what was something that
that you really, as department head, stressed?
Of course, particularly in the early days, people without an A&M degree.
Because for at least the first 10 years or so,
hardly ever was anybody with an A&M degree even seriously considered.
Dr. Hoyle, of course, was our first exception to that.
And the justification for Dr. Hoyle was that he had left this institution, had served in at least three other universities, and so came back to us with an experience base that was
reasonably broad.
There have been several other exceptions in more recent years, but that was one of the criteria that we were very conscious of.
Was that your own personal, or was that for the whole university?
No, no, not the whole university, but that was Dean Hubert's.
Well, it may have been
referred to as a university policy.
But obviously, each college adhered to that policy to a greater or lesser degree, depending upon the direction and priorities of each of the respective deans.
And Dean Hubert was quite firm.
And again, there were exceptions over the years, but by and large,
a real effort to assure that we didn't just employ our own people.
Now, I think that in addition to that, we were always conscious of people wanting to bring in people with good, strong preparation in education administration.
That means that we were conscious particularly of the institution from which they got their doctoral degrees.
We have hardly, but almost entirely without exception, looked for people with administrative experience.
It also had a concern over the years for a more diversified faculty.
It might not always have looked that way.
But we did employ, I think, one of the first minority faculty members in this department of anywhere in the college.
It might have been the second or so, but it was, I think, the first with Dean Hubert's encouragement.
Unfortunately, that person stayed with us only one year.
I think that in the early periods, our emphasis was more upon minority males than on minority females.
Composition of the department faculty now, you can see that we finally found the right road to travel with females as part of our faculty.
But I must say that
I think that kind of diversity has been very significant.
And the interesting thing, I think, is that our faculty in our most recent decisions seem to be very firm in their belief that such decisions to employ such individuals is very important for us.
There's been a lot of stability, has there not, in this department as far as
continuity of the faculty and the number of them being here for many years?
I think so.
We obviously have had some changes, but over the years, I guess probably a greater amount of stability than might be found in many similar departments.
Is there something that you can attribute that to?
Other than the fact that you all were happy?
Oh, I think one would hope that there's a relationship between that and a terrible selection of people.
I suppose that another important factor was the growth of the university.
The fact that it's a little easier for people to stay with an institution in which there is growth, progress, at least some improvement in terms of
faculty salaries, all of those kinds of things.
What about promotion and things?
Was it easier?
I'm not familiar with the tenure track.
Did that have anything to do with promotion?
Yes, I think so.
In the earlier days,
The route to promotion and tenure was, I don't know if I should say relaxed, but at least was a little bit faster, perhaps.
And that has slowed down so that now it is through university policies and procedures, it is a more carefully monitored process.
But I wanted to add one other thing in terms of faculty members remaining in the department.
And I think certainly the growth of the doctoral program, not just expansion of enrollments in the department, but the fact that we grew heavily in the direction of doctoral level work.
And many faculty members prefer to
to be where there is a strong doctoral program.
OK. How about some of the highlights or some of your contributions personally to the growth of the college and the department?
Just personal insights or observations, whatever.

I think one of the things that we tried to do in this department, and hopefully because we supposedly know and understand something about the administrative process, I think we tried to create here what represents a department.
It always seemed to me, as I tried over the years to contact people on this campus, you'd make a contact, you couldn't reach people.
When you reached somebody at the department level, they didn't know where people were.
They didn't know when they would be available.
There seemed to be much more emphasis upon the autonomy of faculty members simply
serving the university with the department responsibilities seemingly not to be a very important factor.
And I don't know that I'm sure you get varying opinions from our own faculty, but I think we've known and understood better than some portions of the university
of what the department's identity perhaps means.

OK. And have you reflected much on the future and what is happening right now in education and some of the reforms and what effect they might be having on the college in, say, the year 2000 or beyond?
Well, I've reflected some.
It may be a little easier to reflect.
You're not department head, and you don't seem to feel as though you have the same kind of responsibility.
But I think in terms of the whole reform movement, that at some point along the line, I began to feel
not as comfortable as I used to.
But all of the people who have become so defensive about the charges against education.
I think that's easier at our level than it is at the public school level where the school superintendent is
is closer to some of the challenges, perhaps.
But I have been less uncomfortable than some people with the demands for change.
And therefore, I think to see education administration function in this department as that
hopefully being able to adjust and to work within some new structures or some new perspectives that I think really have to come.
OK.
I think the people who have always thought, we do have a little outside influence, don't we?
Is that the building downstairs?
I don't know what's going on at the moment.
I think the people who have always thought that teacher salaries and salaries in general and education administration could improve first and that that's going to make us a profession.
I can't see where that point of view has gotten us very far.
It seems to me as though we've

We're now in an era in which we really begin to look upon the kinds of responsibilities in education with a different perspective, and the realization that we need to be 12 months employees, and we need to see our responsibilities somewhat differently.
I don't know that I have said very well what I mean, but at least that's just a point of view that I have.
Dr. Hawkins, in your years here, have you seen any more or less collaborative efforts within this college, among departments, and then within the college with other colleges?
Has it changed any?
I think so.
It's a little hard to measure that because we haven't been writing it down over the years.
But although we've always been encouraged to do that, I think that Dean Corrigan has contributed greatly in terms of that kind of emphasis.
The inquiry structure at least suggests a framework in which that
can take place, and I think to a greater extent than what existed before, it has accomplished its purpose.
I guess that what that has done is to have created some working relationships and so on, which have
been strengthened through more formalized research projects and that sort of thing.
I think there's more of that taking place than used to be.
One of the things that I'm working on at organizational behavior class is decision-making processes and the hierarchy and so forth.
Has that changed much since you've been here?
Or has it always been from the top down?
Well, yes.
Of course, I think it used to be more so under Dean Hubert than it is under Dean Corrigan.
Part of the difference is in their administrative styles, as I mentioned.
Of course, again, I hope those of us in this department understand how that works and can be somewhat more .
There needs to be opportunities for participation.
And I think that in recent years, there's been a good deal more faculty input, faculty participation on the allocation of university research monies, that sort of thing.
of activities during the year and so on.
Most everybody I talk to is a little reluctant to share what they feel has been their greatest contribution.
There's sort of a little reluctance there.
Do you have any ideas looking back what you feel has been maybe your contribution to the growth of this college or this department or both?
I think if there's anything that led to my surviving for a period of time, it may be that in part because I felt myself to be a generalist.
I had quite a lot of years of administrative experience, but I must say
that a department head's position is quite different from anything that I had previously experienced.
But I think a desire to try to get the talents of our faculty, as well as their idiosyncrasies.
Of course.
And that's for all those questions.
When you say that the department head job is quite different, can you elaborate for just a second on that?
What is it about being a department head that is, I have not really visited with too many department heads yet, so.
Well, the comparison that I referred to is that an administrator in

elementary and secondary education despite the fact that almost all administrators come up through the ranks and therefore they have been teachers and despite the fact that there is an assumption and a reality that there is a division between teachers and administrators it seemed to me at least in

the period of time when I served in the public schools, that if it's not a matter of faculty agreeing with what administrators have to do, it seems to me as though there's more of an acceptance, at least.
It's tolerance, whatever.
In this level versus in the public schools?
No, within the public schools.
Oh, I see.
Within the public schools.
In higher education, nobody agrees with anybody about anything.
I think people sort of view that as maybe personally demeaning.
Those are kind of strong words.
I'm just saying them partly for effect.
University faculty can sit around for hours and debate something and never end up with any kind of decision.
And one thing that I guess I have had to sort of become accustomed to and wish that I could change but never could, it was that tendency.
a child trying to get approval from a parent, there's always one more reason why something can't be done.
And university faculties, I think, are sort of like that.
There's always one more point of view to be added.
So we're never short of points of view.
But you do it very good naturedly.
OK, and finally then, I know you don't have a crystal ball, but do you see anything in the year 2000 and beyond that will be significant in your opinion?
What is going to be different about this college, possibly?
I think that we're going to continue to have a college education.
How about that way?
Because there have been some times, and there are some
some possibilities, you see, that colleges of education are dinosaurs, I guess.
Do you really believe that?
No, but there are lots of people who think that.
And I know one faculty member, this reference to dinosaur is not really my own.
I'm like some other people.
in the federal government that maybe borrowed from others.
